      +/- 46.5). Comparison of modifications II and IV revealed a significant (p <
      0.05) increase of CO2 production on a diet rich in carbohydrates (218 +/- 52.0
      vs. 202 +/- 42.3). The energy output at rest (1674 +/- 389.6 vs. 1661 +/- 378.7),
